

2/13/2021 - Turnery operator and switch statements
-Turnery operator can be used only instead of if-else statements
-It can not be used for if-else if-else stamements
-It can not be used for nested if-else statements

		/* instead of if else, ternary operator can be used
        if(number1 > number2){
            distance = number1 - number2;
        }
        else{
            distance = number2 - number1;
        }
        */
        
        distance = number1 > number2 ? number1 - number2 : number2 - number1;


 -> Comparing String
 == can not be used for equal when it is String
equals()

equalsIgnoreCase()


SWITCH Statements
-It is kind of an if else statement but based on "cases" 

Syntax:
switch(expression) { 
	case value: 
	// code to be executed

break; // optional

	case value : 
	// code to be executed

break; // optional

default: // Optional 

	// code to be executed
}


NOTE: We usually use switch statements if we know the certain number of cases such as A week has 7 days and each day can be considered as a case (So, 7 cases)

Otherwise we would use if-else if-else statements

NOTE: Switch is faster than if-else if-else statements






